Kill the session after encrypting 2^47 blocksBoth the privacy and the authenticity properties of OCB degrade asn per s^2 / 2^128, where s is the total number of blocks that then adversary acquires.... In order to ensure that s^2 / 2^128 remainsn small, a given key should be used to encrypt at most 2^48 blocks (2^55n bits or 4 petabytes)nn-- http://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-krovetz-ocb-03nnWe deem it unlikely that a legitimate user will send 4 PB through a Moshnsession.  If it happens, we simply kill the session.  The server andnclient use the same key, so we actually need to die after 2^47 blocks.nnCloses #77.n

Linux: Use our own signalfd wrapper, rather than libstddjbselfpipe already does a fine job of interfacing to signalfd.  But Debian andnUbuntu want us to depend on the skalibs-dev package rather than build libstddjbnourselves.  That would be fine except that skalibs-dev has static librariesnonly, and they aren't built with -fPIC.  This interferes with buildingnmosh-{client,server} as position-independent executables, which is a desirablensecurity measure.nnSo we have our own wrapper, which invokes either signalfd or selfpipe. Fall back to naive built-in byte-swap routinesEL5 lacks htobe64 and friends.  Using its byteswap.h requires an endiannessncheck in our headers, which is fragile and compiler-dependent. Don't leak utmpx entries on shutdown.As far as I know, for all implementations of libutempter, thenutempter_remove_added_record() function depends on the file descriptornpassed to utempter_add_record() to still be valid. The reason for this,nis that this file descriptor is propagated to the setuid utility that isnresponsible for modifying utmpx.nnModify the code to remove the utmpx entry before closing thenpseudo-terminal master device. While there, simply usenutempter_remove_record(), which takes the file descriptor explicitly.nThe advantage is that this prevents potential foot-shooting in thenfuture. Visual inspection of the source code will make it more obviousnthat utempter depends on the file descriptor.nnCloses #179.n

Timestamp: Prevent integer overflow on Darwin PPC 32-bitA Darwin PPC 32-bit user observes huge values numer == 1000000000 andndenom == 18431683 returned from mach_timebase_info().  For thesenvalues, mach_absolute_time() * numer overflows uint64_t every 1000.82nseconds, and 1000000 * denom always overflows uint32_t, with theneffect of making time run backwards at -11190660 times its usualnspeed.nnThis bug was masked on Darwin x86 64-bit, where numer == denom == 1.nnFix it by doing the conversion with double arithmetic instead.nnCloses #479.nnSigned-off-by: Anders Kaseorg <andersk@mit.edu>n

Isolated algorithmic improvements.* Fix inefficient STL use around Parser::UTF8Parser.n* Reduce typeid() usage, change some of it to a virtual methodn* Do multiple-line scrolls as a single moven

Change Framebuffer's containers/methods to improve performance.* Reduce the size of Terminal::Cell.n* Change colors and attributes in Terminal::Rendition to bitfields/bitmask.n* Change Cells to use UTF-8 strings instead of vector<wchar_t>.  Store Rows in a vector instead of a deque.n* Add various Framebuffer::append() methods for more efficient passing of single and repeated characters.n* Change title/icon strings from deques to a vector typedef-- this is more for tidiness than any real performance.n

Rework Terminal::Display to improve performance and treat passed Framebuffers as const.* Refactor put_cell() and parts of new_frame(), and associated state, into put_row().n* Optimize display and line wrap handling code/output.n* Make last_frame a const ref, to eliminate a costly copy of the framebuffer on every screen refresh.n* In new_frame()'s scroll optimization, don't copy rows, use pointers instead.n* Don't check entire frame buffer for scrolling if first line hasn't scrolled.n* Add a generation counter on Row objects to allow quicker/better identification of scroll regionsn* Use at() for bounds-checking on framebuffers, because they can be resized.n* Copy and resize scroll buffer on window resize.n
Make Terminal::Framebuffer::Rows shared and copy-on-write.* Support both std:: and std::tr1:: shared_ptr. FreeBSD 10 now uses C++11 by default.n* Remove Framebuffer pointers in STMClientn

Avoid wcwidth(), wcrtomb() and mbrtowc() on ASCII/ISO8859-1 characters.ASCII <-> UTF has trivial mappings. Update send/ack timers on empty diffThe root problem here is that writes to the frame buffer may alter it,nbut leave it with the same contents as before, and the diff betweennthe two states is the empty string.  With the dirty-rows,nsmart-pointer changes to Framebuffer, it is easy to run into thisnsituation.  This got Network::TransportSender confused about timeouts,nand mosh-server would spin.nnThe theoretically correct fix would be to have operator==() exactlyncorrespond to diff(otherstate).empty().  I have partly implementednthis (and may yet finish) but it's not trivial to get right.nnThis is a much simpler fix that simply attempts to correctly updatentimers when two framebuffers are different and an empty diff isngenerated.n

The build log is still separate.nnThis is not yet final, it deploys to cgull/mosh and notnmobile-shell/mosh.nnIt should not affect Linux or OS X CI builds (other than the change tonthe Travis Xcode 7.1 image).nnIncluded changes:nnThe Travis Xcode 7 image seems to have added tmux while we were gone,nbreaking our Homebrew setup.nnThere seems to be no clean reliable way to determine whether anHomebrew package is installed or needs updating.  Reinstalling is lessnefficient but seems to work reliably.nnThe OS X build is now split between four files:nn.travis.yml contains Travis-specific CI/release build configuration.nnmacosx/brew.sh contains Homebrew-specific package manager installs andnreporting.nnmacosx/osx-xcode.sh contains Apple-specific OS/X and Xcode reporting.nnmacosx/build.sh does the actual package build.n

Memory Alignment issues on ARM processorsUnaligned data on ARM architectures do not perform efficiently unalignednmemory access, and in the case of ARMv7 and iOS it completely breaks. The OCBnalgorithm dereferences a uint64x2_t pointer, and is replaced by anmemcpy to avoid penalties when trying to align it.nnMore info https://brewx.qualcomm.com/bws/content/gi/common/appseng/en/knowledgebase/docs/kb95.htmln

Reformat printed strings in sourceConsolidate multiple printfs.nBreak up multiline strings with string concatentation, for bettern clarity and shorter lines.nUse fputs where appropriate.nnThis also has the benefit of producing a single constant string withncopyright and versions in the binaries.n
Don't do prediction on large pastes into mosh-client.Fixes #482, memory use blowup on large pastes.  mosh is still pretty slownabout copying pastes through, though.n

Allow non-inserting prediction.This may be useful for users who find prediction's activity right ofnthe cursor distracting.nnPrediction underscoring is still a little weird sometimes, it replaysna history of known/unknown changes as acks come in from the server.n
--predict-overwrite was still inserting one column sometimes.  Fix.
Rename and document --predict-overwrite.
Fix utempter #ifdefs.
Add missing shared::make_shared<T>()

remove unneeded new/delete in Compressor

Use shared_ptr and references for Actions.This slows terminal emulation slightly.n
Simplify some conditionals in terminaloverlay.cc.
Remove unused Action::operator==Signed-off-by: Anders Kaseorg <andersk@mit.edu>n
Improve targets for existing static checkers.

Split a long printf format string.

Apply latest consecutive resize, not earliest.If there are consecutive resize events in the userstream to be applied innserve, we should apply the last/latest one in the sequence, not thenfirst/earliest one.nnThis fixes a problem where a flurry of resize events (eg, generatednby a window manager resizing the client), can cause mosh to have annout-of-date idea as to what the physical geometry of the window is.n
configure.ac: Fix underquoted AC_HELP_STRING callSigned-off-by: Anders Kaseorg <andersk@mit.edu>n

configure: Add --enable-static-LIBRARY options for selective static linkingStatically linking mosh-server with glibc isnu00e2u0080u0099t a great idea fornvarious reasons (nsswitch modules, locale format incompatibilities).nBut we can provide most of the benefits of static linking by allowingnspecific library dependencies to be linked statically using -Bstaticnand -Bdynamic.  The full set is enabled bynn./configure --enable-static-librariesnnwhich is equivalent tonn./configure --enable-static-libstdc++ --enable-static-libgcc n  --enable-static-utempter --enable-static-zlib --enable-static-curses n  --enable-static-crypto --enable-static-protobufnnand results in binaries whose only runtime library dependencies arenprovided with libc:nn$ ldd src/frontend/mosh-servernlinux-vdso.so.1 (0x00007ffe0b377000)nlibutil.so.1 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libutil.so.1 (0x00007fa0d9970000)nlibm.so.6 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libm.so.6 (0x00007fa0d97e3000)nlibpthread.so.0 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libpthread.so.0 (0x00007fa0d97c2000)nlibc.so.6 => /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libc.so.6 (0x00007fa0d95d8000)n/lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 (0x00007fa0d9f6a000)nnSigned-off-by: Anders Kaseorg <andersk@mit.edu>n
configure: Another flag for macOS distcheck: -Wno-error=nested-anon-typesSigned-off-by: Anders Kaseorg <andersk@mit.edu>n

Fix Appveyor build.Change the openssl-devel package to libssl-devel.  Cygwin still has annobsolete (essentially virtual) package for openssl-devel, but itndoesn't seem to work properly on Appveyor's Cygwin install.nnProtobuf >= 3.6.0 requires C++11, which I added support for last year.nBut when I did that, I requested strict ANSI C++ compatibility, whichncauses Cygwin/newlib's libc feature test macros to be set to disablen(at least) POSIX.1 extensions.  Let the Autoconf macro use its defaultninstead (prefer GNU/extended C++, accept anything).n
